The Amazon rainforest are not the “lungs of the world” as several environmentalists have pointed out in the past month. Spreading such lies has dangerous implications! 

Let’s begin with an example:
My mother, being the environment enthusiast that she is, once suggested that it might be easier to “save the trees” if we told the majorly daft religious populace of India that cutting trees was against the religion they practice. While it is easy to see why spreading such a lie might work in the short run (even the Sad-Gurus of the world have been running similar campaigns that provides easy publicity in this era of [woke advertising]{link | url = https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/jun/06/progressive-advertising-fake-woke}), the long term sanity is in approaching the situation by the scientific method.

The tree-religion case, driven by ignorance and lies, can soon turn into rituals that require these religiously significant trees to be dumped into fresh water rivers, destroying delicate ecosystems by planting invasive species of plants, driving people to a mad civil war by giving them reasons like “Banyan is my mother. Those who kill my mother would be lynched”. The list of idiotic repercussions of such “noble lies” are quite unimaginably endless.

